Tina's 2016 Election Project

The 2016 US presidential election result was a surprise to many, arguably including both candidates and campaigns themselves. Although national polling did show that the race would be very close, most polls still gave Clinton a higher likelihood of winning, and most media commentators and even most voters expected Clinton to win.

Given the fact that President Obama won re-election in 2012 by a comfortable margin in the Electoral College, I would like to look at data on the 2016 election results with a specific focus on explaining why counties that voted for Obama in 2012 then went to Trump in 2016. It is well known that some states--be they "blue" or "red"--are more likely to vote for candidates of a certain political party. But the causes of changes in so-called "swing" areas are less well understood, so I would like to see how well data can predict the changes between these two elections, rather than predict the election result itself.

Data Sources

Data on the 2012 and 2016 electoral results by county is available here, and was originally compiled from data provided by The Guardian and townhall.com.

County-level data on socio-economic factors, such as income levels, racial and ethnic demographics, and economic indicators, are available here and were originally collected and published by the US Census Bureau.

Data on turnout levels by county in 2012 and 2016 was compiled and published by the US Election Project.

All variables included are from indicators collected between 2012 and 2016, since any data from before 2012 is too far removed from my aim of looking at changes between 2012 and 2016.

Initial Feature Engineering and Dataset Building

First, I combined data at the county level (one dataset about election results, and one dataset about demographic information) into one dataset, joining data about each county based on its FIPS code, the federal code identifying each county. I transformed some "count" variables, including number of veterans and number of building permits issued per year, into "percent" variables by dividing by the county population, to ensure that variables are comparable across all counties regardless of county size. I then added two categorical variables, region and color, to identify the part of the country in which each county is located (based on the state), and to label whether the county is 'blue' (voted Democratic in both elections), 'red' (voted Republican in both), or 'purple' (voted for candidates of different parties). PurpleD is a county that swung from Republican to Democratic, and PurpleR is a county that swung from Democratic to Republican.

Finally, I created the key variable to be examined, the change in margin. Margin is percentage of voters voting Democratic minus the percentage voting Republican. So a negative margin impies a Republican electoral victory, and a positive margin means Democratic victory. Likewise, a negative "change" in margin is the number of percetage points "more Republican" a county voted, while a positive change in margin number is the number of percentage points "more Democratic" a county voted.

Unfortunately, data on turnout levels--percentages of eligible voters who actually came out to vote--are available only at the state level, rather than at the county level. So I created new variables in the county turnout dataset, first to represent the turnout level (votes cast over eligible voting population) in each election, and then a final variable to indicate the change in turnout between 2012 and 2016 (the difference in the turnout percentage levels in each election). I also added a label, "red", "blue", or "purple" to each state, to identify states that voted for the Republican or Democratic presidential candidiate in both elections (red or blue) and swing states, all of which voted for Pres. Obama in 2012 and for Trump in 2016.

I then joined the turnout dataset and the county-level dataset by state, so that each county is labeled with the average turnout change across its state, as well as its state electoral result (red/blue/purple).

regional <- function (x) {
   region <- ifelse(x %in% c("ME", "NH", "VT", "NY", "MA", "CT", "RI", "NJ", "MD", "DE", "DC"), "Atlantic", 
                ifelse(x %in% c("WV", "KY", "TN"), "Appalacia",
                ifelse(x %in% c("VA", "NC", "SC", "MS", "GA", "AL", "FL", "AK"), "South",
                ifelse(x %in% c("PA", "OH", "MI", "WI", "IN", "IL", "MO", "IA", "MN"), "Midwest",
                ifelse(x %in% c("TX", "LA", "OK"), "Central",
                ifelse(x %in% c("KS", "NE", "ND", "SD", "WY", "MT", "ID"), "Plains",
                ifelse(x %in% c("CO", "NM", "AZ", "UT", "NV"), "Southwest",
                ifelse(x %in% c("CA", "OR", "WA"), "Pacific",
                "Noncontinental"
                         ))))))))
    return(region) 
}
dat$region <- regional(dat$State)

votecolor <- function (x, y) {
    ifelse(x < 0 & y < 0, "red", 
    ifelse(x > 0 & y > 0, "blue", 
    ifelse(x > 0 & y < 0, "purpleD", "purpleR"
    )))
}
dat$countycolor <- votecolor(dat$DRmarg2016, dat$DRmarg2012)

margchange <- function (x, y) {
    x <- x + 1  # add one to each margin so that all values are positive, in order to calculate the change
    y <- y + 1
    change <- (x - y)*100
    return(change)
}
dat$margchg <- margchange(dat$DRmarg2016, dat$DRmarg2012)

Turnout Hypothesis

Before we focus in at the county level, I want to test my initial hypothesis that the unexpected election results were due to lower voter turnout in the 2016 election than in 2012. Since it seems unlikely to me that many voters who voted for President Obama in 2012 then voted for Trump in 2016, I wonder whether the cause of the election result was that people who didn't like either candidate in 2016 just stayed home instead of voting.

In [5]:
print(mean(dat$turnout2016))   #  How did national turnout change between 2012 and 2016?
print(mean(dat$turnout2012))

The mean turnout rate per state in the 2016 election was 59%, not much lower than the mean rate of 60% in the 2012 election. But let's take a closer look at the swing states:

This seems to support my hypothesis about decreased turnout being related to the election results, even though turnout at the national level did not change much.

To test this hypothesis with a bit more rigor, I will conduct a one-sample t-test for each of the swing state turnout level changes to see if it is statistically greater or lesser than the average in turnout change across all states.

Exploring Changes in Victory Margins

Now let's turn to the victory margins (again, margin = % voting Democratic minus % voting Republican) to visualize the changes between the 2012 and 2016 elections. First, let's look at a scatterplot of 2016 margins over 2012 margins by county, factored by the region of the country. Then we'll look at boxplots of the changes in margin in red and blue states, compared to swing states.

In [8]:
ggplot(combinedat, aes(x=combinedat$DRmarg2012, y=combinedat$DRmarg2016)) + geom_point(aes(color = factor(combinedat$region))) + geom_smooth(method = "loess") + ggtitle("Presidential Victory Margins in 2012 and 2016")

This plot shows some interesting patterns. First, we can see that the majority of counties in both elections had negative margins, meaning more counties voted Republican. This fits with the known trend that many rural, low-population counties typically vote for Republican candidates; though the electoral college system is supposed to result in the candidate with more total votes winning the election. We also see with the help of the loess line that in general, victory margins in 2016 were about 2 percentage points (-0.2 intercept on the y-axis) more Republican than in 2012.

The coloration by region of the country shows that many Midwestern and Appalacian counties are in the lower band of the distribution, meaning that they voted relatively "more Republican" in 2016 over 2012 than other states did. The green Midwestern dots are closer to zero, meaning that their margins were much tighter, and more Democratic, in the 2012 election, and then they changed the most of all regions towards the Republican candidate in 2016. The South and Central (Texas, Lousiana & Oklahoma) counties seem to be on the upper band of the distribution, meaning that even though they mostly voted Republican in both elections, they actually did not become as much "more Republican" than other regions did. Finally, it seems that most of the "outlier" counties that voted Republican in both elections, but voted much "less Republican" in 2016 than in 2012, were in the Southwest and the Plains.

In [9]:
ggplot(combinedat, aes_string("countycolor")) + geom_bar() + ggtitle("Counts of County Results")
ggplot(combinedat, aes_string("countycolor", "margchg")) + geom_boxplot() + ggtitle("Changes in Victory Margins, 2012-2016")

We see in the above images that only about 200+ counties swung from Democratic to Republican candidiates from 2012 to 2016, though this was enough to change the election result. Only a handful of counties swung from Republican to Democratic. The boxplots show that the spread of changes in victory margins was much wider in red counties than in others, with some counties that voted Republican in both elections still seeing a movement of more than 25 percentage points "more Democratic". We see this in the first scatterplot, where the dispersion on the bottom half of points is greater than the top half.

Something that should be of concern to the Democratic party is that the mean of changes in margins even in 'blue' counties was below zero. This means that even in counties that voted for the Democratic candidiate in both 2012 and 2016, thre was overall movement towards voting "more Republican" in 2016 (since a negative number for the change in margin doesn't necessarily mean that the county voted Republican, but that it voted "more Republican" than it did before).

Next, let's look at the socio-economic and demographic data available by county, as well as how these variables correlate with the victory margin changes. Since there are many variables available, let's look first at economic, and then socio-demographic and political variables (keeping our key variable, margin change, in all comparisons).

Victory margin changes do not appear very correlated to population size, density, or population growth rates by county. Education attainment rates seem to be correlatd with each other, and with rates of veteraans in the county, which is interesting and possibly related to GI Bill benefits.

Change in victory margins looks correlated with the percentage of residents with bachelor's degree by county--we will examine this more closely soon.

Moving on to social variables:

In [12]:
pairs(~ ., data = combinedat[, dem_cols])

Percentages of residents in different racial groups are strongly correlated to each other by definition, since the total percentage is limited at 100%. Percentage of Hispanic residents is correlated with speaking another language at home and with percentage of foreign-born population. The variability of victory margin changes shows an opposite pattern in relation to percentages of white residents and percentages of non-white residents: it shows high variability in counties with high percentages of white residents, and low variability in counties with low percentages of white residents.

Is this because counties with low percentages of white residents typically vote for Democratic candidates, and so have less room for changes in victory margins? Let's examine the plot more closely, factored by 'blue' states:

In [13]:
ggplot(combinedat, aes_string("PercWhite2014", 'margchg')) +
    geom_point(aes(color = factor(countycolor))) + scale_color_manual(values=c('blue', 'purple', 'purple', 'red'), guide = FALSE) + geom_smooth(method = "loess") + ggtitle("Margin Changes by % of White Residents")

This supports that hypothesis: the vast majority of counties where less than 50% of residents are white are 'blue', or voted for Democrats in both 2012 and 2016, and show less dispersion of margin changes than counties with high percentages of white residents.

Since I am trying to focus on 'swing' counties that changed from Democratic to Republican election results, it looks like it makes sense to focus on counties with high percentages of white residents, since more racially diverse counties are predominantly 'blue' and had smaller changes in victory margins.

The loess fitted line shows that there is not a strong relationship between percentage of population that is white and victory margin changes in counties with less than about 80% white residents, but a much stronger correlation in counties with greater than 80% white residents.

Let's examine this a bit more closely, and add in the factor of percentage of residents with a bachelor's degree.

Modeling Electoral Outcomes

Now that we have identified some key variables, namely, region, median household income, percentage of residents with bachelor's degrees, and percentage of residents who are white, we can see how well these variables and their interactions can be used to model both the change in victory margin (using a regression model) and to predict which counties will be swing counties (using a classification model).

Because the benefits of creating a predictive model on the election are mostly related to identifying the most important or influential variables, rather than creating the 'best' model, I will focus on interpretible models. A 'black box' model that predicts the election result well might be useful for betting on election results, but it is not useful for political analysts or operatives trying to identify which factors to focus on to try to win future elections. I will therefore use linear (or log) regressions to predict both swing counties and changes in victory margins.

Classification: Prediting Swing Counties

The count chart above showed that there were roughly 225 counties that 'swung' from Obama in 2012 to Trump in 2016. As we saw in the initial margin distribution chart, they are mostly in the key swing region of the Midwest:

In [23]:
swing <- combinedat[combinedat$countycolor=="purpleR",]
ggplot(swing, aes_string("region")) + geom_bar() + ggtitle("Swing Counties by Region")

Since there are about 225 D-to-R swing counties out of a total of 3109 counties, we are trying to predict a result that is seen in just 7% of the data. So I will compare the performance of modeling the base dataset with that of a dataset that has been SMOTE adjusted to increase the importance of the 'swing', R-to-D counties in the model. Since the six swing states have 99 total electoral college votes, or 18% of the total electoral college of 538 votes, I create a dummy variable to identify 'purpleR' counties and use a SMOTE increase of 100% to effectively double the 'value' of the original 225 counties in the dataset to be closer to the value of the swing states in the electoral college.

Region is a categorical variable; all other variables are numeric. These include median housing values, median household income, percent of population with high school diplomas, percent with bachelor's degrees, percent who are veterans, percent who are white (I will not include other racial variables since they are so correlated with percent who are white), and change in turnout since 2012. I will also add an interaction variable, percent of white residents * percent with bachelor's degree, to capture the interaction observed above.

Before modeling how well these variables predict swing category and margin change, let's check to see if they are reasonably normally distributed:

In [24]:
combinedat$racebach <- combinedat$PercWhite2014*combinedat$PercBachDegree2013

               "PercWhite2014", "racebach", "turnoutChange", "margchg")

It looks like median housing value and median household income, percentages of residents with high school diplomas and bachelor's degrees, percent of residents who are white all have fairly skewed distributions. So I will make a natural-log transformation of these variables prior to modeling. Percentage of veteran residents, turnout chages, the race-education interaction, and margin change (the outcome variable for a regression model, not included in a classification model) are fairly normally distributed. Finally I normalize all numeric variables, and then tune parameters to determine the best parameters for a log-linear classification model to predict whether or not a county is a swing R-to-D county.

Model Results

The best-fit two-class log regression model acheived a precision rate of 1.0 and accuracy of 0.93 by predicting that no counties would swing from D to R. The most important feature was region, with all other features scoring a zero in importance in the Permutation Feature Importance analysis in Azure ML. Applying the optimal parameters identified by tuning to a model using the entire dataset, rather than a set split for training, resulted in the same outcome, predicting all negatives. There is likely not enough variability in the existing county-level dataset to create a useful predictive model for such a low-incidence outcome variable, since only ~220 counties out of 3109 were the key swing counties.

Regression: Predicting Victory Margin Changes

I then use the same variables in a linear regression to observe how much changes in these variable could be expected to affect the change in victory margin in 2016. The best-fit model had an r-squared of 0.64. As was visible in the exploratory analysis, the most important variables affecting the change in victory margin between 2012 and 2016 were the county's region, percentage of residents with bachelor's degrees, the interaction between percentages of white residents & those with bachelor's degrees. Summary of Findings

Overall, this analysis shows the extent of the move in victory margins towards the Republican candidate in 2016, compared to 2012--the movement happened even in 'blue' counties that voted for Democrats in both elections. This change was most pronounced in Midwestern states, and was associated with counties with higher percentages of white residents and lower percentages of residents with bachelor's degrees, though the association is much stronger with the educational than with the racial variable. It is also interesting that with the exceptions of Pennsylvania and Florida, the states that "swung" from President Obama in 2012 to candidate Trump in 2016 saw significant drops in voter turnout between 2012 and 2016 than did other states on average.

An interesting take-away for Democratic strategists looking forward is to focus on Congressional 2018 races in the South, Plains states, and Texas, where the observed increases in Republican victory margins were not as high as those in other regions with the same demographic qualities. In particular, the Southern and Plains states whose electoral margins in the 2012 were much closer to zero (tighter/more competitive races) than those of Texas area counties seem to be promising strategic targets for Democratics.
